ation, of which [Henderson] is the world's foremost psychological interpreter. This material is really the next step after the hero myth that Joseph Campbell has made so popular, and provides an understanding of how not to use the hero myth in an inflated way as a psychology of mastery, but as an attainment progressively to be died beyond. [Henderson] is helped by the presence of Maud Oakes, who is a trained anthropologist with exquisite taste in her choice of mythic materials and respect for their original contexts."--John Beebe  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aDeathxMythology. 0aDeathxReligious aspectsvComparative studies. 0aRegeneration (Theology)vComparative studies. 0aResurrectionvComparative studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Folklore & Mythology.2bisacsh  aAdonis.  aAphrodite and Adonis.  aBalder.  aBaptism.  aChuang Tzu.  aCompassion in Buddhism.  aDrowning.  aEleusinian Mysteries.  aEreshkigal.  aEvergreen tree.  aFenris Wolf.  aFertility myths.  aGilgamesh.  aHeracles.  aHermes.  aHorus.  aInitiation.  aIzanagi.  aKaliyuga.  aKarma.  aMagic flight of shamans.  aMistletoe.  aNachiketas and Yama.  aOld Testament.  aOsiris.  aPersephone.  aRagnarok.  aReincarnation.  aShamanism.  aShiva.  aSymbols.  aTammuz.  aThoth.  aVishnu.1 aHenderson, Joseph L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOakes, Maud, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aOakes, Maud, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691216171zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691216171423Coveruhttps://ww